At 12:03 23/05/2001 -0400, you wrote:
&gt;Just about everyone&#39;s weighed in on this topic.  It&#39;s an interesting one.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;
&gt;I&#39;d like to remind that the reason for the name &quot;unit test&quot; is that it
&gt;refers to the _scope_ of the components that are being tested, relative to
&gt;the entire system.  The term &quot;unit testing&quot; should not imply anything too
&gt;prescriptive about the strategies employed to test thoroughly at that scope,
&gt;though as others have stated, there are guidelines.  In object oriented
&gt;programming the &quot;unit&quot; scope is often a class, but is also often a single
&gt;method or a cluster of closely related classes.  Truly, a program can be
&gt;broken into even smaller units - expressions and statements - but everyone
&gt;agrees this is too granular for testing.
&gt;
&gt;Also recall that the test of whether we&#39;ve tested _enough_ should be code
&gt;coverage analysis of the component/subsystem/system under test when run
&gt;against our test suite.  If testing all the public and protected methods
&gt;also happens to test your private methods and exception handlers thoroughly,
&gt;then you&#39;re all set, but you don&#39;t know that unless you have extremely
&gt;simple applications, or you are doing coverage analysis.  Anyway, it is
&gt;unsafe to conclude a priori that public API testing is all that is needed;
&gt;each situation should determine the tools and strategies used.
&gt;
&gt;I have two examples to offer that may help when you&#39;re in a tough situation
&gt;where testing private methods or protected classes.
&gt;
&gt;One is a private field accessor class, the other is a technique.
&gt;
&gt;I&#39;m attaching the FieldAccessor, which is mainly from Larman and Guthrie&#39;s
&gt;Java 2 performance and idiom book.  Personally, I have yet to need this
&gt;class for anything, but I thought I&#39;d pass it along.  It&#39;s javadoc&#39;ed.
&gt;
&gt;The technique is one that I have found useful at least once, which is to put
&gt;a public static inner class that extends junit.framework.TestCase in the
&gt;class under test.  This gives the inner class full access to the outer
&gt;class&#39;s private methods and members, while allowing the inner class to be an
&gt;instance of a JUnit test case.  I sent an example of this to this list a few
&gt;weeks ago.  Another handy thing is that when you compile the outer class,
&gt;the inner test case is produced in a separate class file which can be safely
&gt;deleted when packaging the outer class for production (because the outer
&gt;class makes no references to the static inner class).
&gt;
&gt;Scott Stirling
&gt;Macromedia
